Here's a multi-form question based on the provided LaTeX code and explanation:

Question: Which LaTeX code snippet would correctly align equality signs vertically when one equation has an underset explanation, without using \phantom?

A) \begin{align*}
     a &= b + c\\
     d &= e + f + d
   \end{align*}

B) \begin{align*}
     a &\underset{\text{explanation}}{=} b + c\\
     d &= e + f + d
   \end{align*}

C) \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5}\setlength{\arraycolsep}{0pt}
   \begin{array}{r >{{}}c<{{}} l}
     a &\underset{\text{explanation}}{=} & b + c\\
     d &= & e + f + d
   \end{array}

D) \begin{align*}
     a &\underset{\text{explanation}}{=} b + c\\
     d &\underset{\phantom{\text{explanation}}}{=} e + f + d
   \end{align*}

Correct Answer: C

Explanation: Option C uses the array environment with custom column specifications and adjustments to arraystretch and arraycolsep. This approach aligns the equality signs vertically without relying on \phantom, resulting in a more elegant and flexible solution. Option A doesn't include the underset explanation. Option B doesn't align the equality signs properly. Option D uses \phantom, which is less elegant when multiple undersets are involved.

